Figma has always¬†encouraged collaboration¬†between developers and designers. It strives on an endless treasury of community-made plugins. Need¬†3D elements?¬†There‚Äôs a plugin for that.¬†Need¬†abstract SVGs?¬†There‚Äôs a plugin for that, too.



 That said, the design part of Figma has always been relatively static ‚Äî always working with unmovable rectangles connected to each other through predefined user interactions. But what if I told you that your designs could suddenly come to life ‚Äî that they could be animated, interactive, and even stateful? Then, what would separate concept from implementation?



 Figma¬†announced in June¬†that it‚Äôs bringing JavaScript-powered widgets to the table. Now, designers have can browse and implement logic-driven components straight in Figma!



 Say hello to¬†the Widgets API! You want to know what it is and how to use it? That‚Äôs exactly what we‚Äôre going to do together in this post.






 Figma widgets open up tons of possibilities


 Imagine that you‚Äôre working around the clock with your partner to design a large restaurant application. You‚Äôre both already collaborating on the same Figma board; both of you are sharing the exact same document with changes happening on the fly.



 Surely, you already know that collaboration involves more that just the design process:



 project management,hosting polls to gather votes,importing and visualizing mock data,and perhaps even playing a multiplayer game to cool-off after many hours of work.



 We just require one person to manage everything and send-out links to other members of the group. But oh, that‚Äôs not very efficient, is it?



 Well, that‚Äôs where widgets come into play. We can conceivably do all of that ‚Äî yes, everything ‚Äîwithout ever leaving Figma.



 Here are just a few of the ways you might want to use widgets in Figma:



 Creating tasks for¬†Jira¬†and¬†AsanaCreating¬†issues in GitHubDisplaying¬†Dynamic DataRecording¬†voice memosCreating¬†task listsWasting time¬†Playing¬†Tic-Tac-ToeTracking¬†activitiesCreating¬†timers



 The list goes¬†on and on. As you can tell, there‚Äôs already a plethora of widgets that you can freely use in your documents. In fact, you can add Widgets straight to your board from the Widgets menu (Shift+I).



 But we‚Äôre not here to learn how to use widgets, because that‚Äôs easy. Let us do what we do best: we‚Äôre gonna create our own Figma widget! This one will be inspired by¬†Chris Coyier‚Äôs design quotes website. We‚Äôll take the API, feed it into the widget, then display random design quotes directly in Figma.






 Here‚Äôs what we need


 I don‚Äôt like to be the bearer of bad news, but in order to develop widgets, you must be on Windows or Mac. Linux users, I‚Äôm sorry, but you‚Äôre out of luck. (You could still¬†use a VM¬†if you want to follow along.)



 We‚Äôre gonna¬†download the Figma Desktop¬†application. The simplest way to get started is by generating a widget template, straight from the app.







 Let‚Äôs create a new board by opening the widgets menu (Shift+¬†I), switching to the¬†Development¬†tab, and creating a new item.







 Following that, Figma will prompt you to name the new widget and decide whether it‚Äôs more tailored towards¬†design boards or FigJam boards¬†too. The former option is sufficient for the purposes of this article.







 And the customization doesn‚Äôt end here; Figma will also give you the option to start with a pre-made counter widget or an iFrame-enabled alternative that also gives you access to the Canvas and Fetch APIs (as well as all other browser APIs). We‚Äôll go with the simple ‚ÄúEmpty‚Äù option, but we‚Äôll eventually modify it ourselves to make use of the Fetch API.



 You‚Äôll then be prompted to save your new widget project to a special directory in your system. Once that‚Äôs done, launch your terminal and direct it to that folder. Don‚Äôt run any commands yet ‚Äî we‚Äôll do that later and purposefully get an error with the goal of learning more about the Widgets API.


 Designing the widget






 We‚Äôre pulling the design straight from¬†Chris Coyier‚Äôs design quotes website. So, let‚Äôs go there and dive into by firing up DevTools.









 The two key shortcuts that I‚Äôm using here are¬†Ctrl+Shift+C¬†(or¬†Cmd+Shift+C) to toggle the ‚ÄúPick element‚Äù tool, and¬†Shift+Click¬†to change the color format to HEX code. We‚Äôre doing this to learn about the colors, fonts, font weights and font sizes used in Chris‚Äôs website. All this information is critical to build a closely-resembling widget in Figma, which will be our next step! You can¬†grab the designed component¬†and use it in your own canvas.



 I won‚Äôt go into much detail here as this article‚Äôs main topic is building widgets by writing code. But I can‚Äôt stress enough how important it is to take good care of your¬†widgets‚Äô style‚Ä¶ CSS-Tricks already has a plethora of¬†design-oriented Figma tutorials; you won‚Äôt regret adding them to your reading list.


 Creating the layout for our widget


 With design out of the way, it‚Äôs time to take our programming fingers out and start building the gears of our widget.



 It‚Äôs very interesting how Figma translates its design building blocks to React-like components. Frame elements with the auto-layout feature, for example, are represented as the¬†<AutoLayout />¬†component in code. In addition to that, we‚Äôll be using two more components:¬†<Text />¬†and¬†<SVG />.



 Take a look at my Figma board‚Ä¶ I‚Äôm precisely asking you to focus on the object tree. It‚Äôs what we need to be able to translate our widget design to JSX code.







 As you can see, our design quotes widget demands three components to be imported. That‚Äôs a decent number of components considering that the¬†full API¬†only contains eight layer-based nodes. But as you‚Äôll soon see, these modules are more than sufficient to craft all kinds of layouts.



 // code.tsx
 const { widget } = figma;
 const { AutoLayout, Text, SVG } = widget;



 And with this, we have all we need to go ahead and build the skeleton of our widget like we would in React:



 function QuotesWidget() {
   const quote = `...`;
   const author = `...`;

   return (
     <AutoLayout>
       <SVG />
       <AutoLayout>
         <Text>{quote}</Text>
         <Text>‚Äî {author}</Text>
       </AutoLayout>
       <SVG />
     </AutoLayout>
   );
 }

 widget.register(QuotesWidget);



 This code is very confusing, to say the least. Right now, we can‚Äôt tell the design layers apart. Thankfully, we‚Äôre able to easily solve this issue through the use of the¬†name¬†property.



 <AutoLayout name={"Quote"}>
   <SVG name={"LeftQuotationMark"} />
   <AutoLayout name={"QuoteContent"}>
     <Text name={"QuoteText"}>{quote}</Text>
     <Text name={"QuoteAuthor"}>‚Äî {author}</Text>
   </AutoLayout>
   <SVG name={"RightQuotationMark"} />
 </AutoLayout>;



 And, of course, we still can‚Äôt see our quotation mark SVGs, so let‚Äôs work on fixing that. The¬†<SVG/>¬†component accept a¬†srcproperty that takes the source code for an SVG element. There isn‚Äôt much to say on this one, so let‚Äôs keep it simple and jump straight back to code:



 const leftQuotationSvgSrc = `<svg width="117" height="103" viewBox="0 0 117 103" fill="none" xmlns="<http://www.w3.org/2000/svg>">
   // shortened for brevity
 </svg>`;
 const rightQuotationSvgSrc = `<svg width="118" height="103" viewBox="0 0 118 103" fill="none" xmlns="<http://www.w3.org/2000/svg>">
 // shortened for brevity
 </svg>`;

 function QuotesWidget() {
   return (
     <SVG name={"LeftQuotationMark"} src={leftQuotationSvgSrc} />
     <SVG name={"RightQuotationMark"} src={rightQuotationSvgSrc} />
   );
 }



 I think we can all agree that everything is much clearer now! When we name things, their purpose suddenly becomes much more obvious to the readers of our code.


 Previewing our widget in real-time


 Figma offers a great developer experience when building widgets, including (but not limited to )¬†hot-reloading. With this feature, we‚Äôre able to code and preview changes to our widget in real-time.



 Get started by opening the widgets menu (Shift+I), switching to the development tab and clicking or dragging your new widget to the board. Unable to locate your widget? Don‚Äôt worry, just click on the three-dot menu and import your widget‚Äôs¬†manifest.json¬†file. Yes, that‚Äôs all it takes bring it back to existence!







 Wait, did you get an error message at the bottom of your screen?







 If so, let‚Äôs investigate. Click on ‚ÄúOpen console‚Äù and read what it has to say. If the¬†Open console¬†button is gone, there‚Äôs an alternative way to open the debugging console. Click on the Figma logo, jump to the widgets category and reveal the development menu.







 That error is likely due to the fact that we haven‚Äôt compiled our TypeScript to JavaScript yet. We can do that in the command line by running¬†npm install¬†and¬†npm run watch. (or¬†yarn¬†and¬†yarn watch¬†). No errors this time!



 One more obstacle you might hit is that the widget fails to re-render any time the code is changed. We can easily force our widget to update using the following context menu command:¬†Widgets¬†‚Üí¬†Re-render widget.






 Styling the widget


 As it currently stands, the¬†looks¬†of our widgets are still pretty far from our final goal.







 So how do we style Figma components from code? Maybe with CSS like we would do in a React project? Negative. With Figma widgets,¬†all¬†the styling happens through a set of¬†well-documented props. Lucky for us, these items are named almost¬†identically¬†to their counterparts in Figma.







 We‚Äôll get started by configuring our two¬†<AutoLayout />¬†components. As you can see in the infographic above, prop names are pretty descriptive of their purpose. This makes it easy for us to jump straight into code and start making some changes. I won‚Äôt be showing the whole code again, so please rely on the component names to guide you where the snippets belongs.



 <AutoLayout
   name={"Quote"}
   direction={"horizontal"}
   verticalAlignItems={"start"}
   horizontalAlignItems={"center"}
   spacing={54}
   padding={{
     horizontal: 61,
     vertical: 47,
   }}
 >
   <AutoLayout
     name={"QuoteContent"}
     direction={"vertical"}
     verticalAlignItems={"end"}
     horizontalAlignItems={"start"}
     spacing={10}
     padding={{
       horizontal: 0,
       vertical: 0,
     }}
   ></AutoLayout>
 </AutoLayout>;



 We just made a lot of progress! Let‚Äôs save and jump back to Figma to see how our widget looks like. Remember how Figma reloads widgets automatically upon new changes?







 But it‚Äôs not quite there yet. We must also add a background color to the root component:



 <AutoLayout name={"Quote"} fill={"#ffffff"}>



 Again, take a look at your Figma board and notice how changes can be reflected almost immediately back into the widget.







 Let‚Äôs move along this guide and style the¬†<Text>¬†components.







 After taking a look at the¬†Widgets API documentation, it‚Äôs again clear that property names are almost identical to their counterparts in the Figma app, as can be seen in the infographic above. We‚Äôll also be using values from the last section where we inspected Chris‚Äô website.







 <Text name={'QuoteText'}
   fontFamily={'Lora'}
   fontSize={36}
   width={700}
   fill={'#545454'}
   fontWeight={'normal'}
 >{quote}</Text>

